# ---------------- Step 1: Import Libraries & Load Dataset ----------------
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Load Titanic dataset (make sure titanic.csv is in the same folder)
df = pd.read_csv(r"C:\Users\mpsan\titanic0.csv")

# Display first 5 rows
print("----- First 5 rows -----")
print(df.head())

# Basic info
print("\n----- Info -----")
print(df.info())

# Describe numeric columns
print("\n----- Describe -----")
print(df.describe())

# Counts
print("\n----- Survived Count -----")
print(df['Survived'].value_counts())
print("\n----- Pclass Count -----")
print(df['Pclass'].value_counts())
print("\n----- Sex Count -----")
print(df['Sex'].value_counts())

# ---------------- Step 2: Histograms & Boxplots ----------------
plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
df['Age'].hist()
plt.title("Age Distribution")
plt.xlabel("Age")
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
sns.boxplot(x=df['Fare'])
plt.title("Fare Boxplot")
plt.show()

# Scatterplot Age vs Fare
plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
plt.scatter(df['Age'], df['Fare'])
plt.title("Age vs Fare")
plt.xlabel("Age")
plt.ylabel("Fare")
plt.show()

# ---------------- Step 3: Pairplot & Heatmap ----------------
numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include=['int64','float64']).drop(columns=['Survived'])
pairplot_df = numeric_df.copy()
pairplot_df['Survived'] = df['Survived']

sns.pairplot(pairplot_df, hue='Survived')
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.heatmap(df.select_dtypes(include=['int64','float64']).corr(), annot=True)
plt.title("Correlation Heatmap")
plt.show()

# ---------------- Step 4: Countplots ----------------
plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
sns.countplot(x='Sex', hue='Survived', data=df)
plt.title("Survival by Sex")
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
sns.countplot(x='Pclass', hue='Survived', data=df)
plt.title("Survival by Class")
plt.show()

# ---------------- Step 5: Summary of Findings ----------------
summary = """
Summary of Findings:
- Females survived more than males.
- 1st class passengers had the highest survival.
- Age distribution is mostly between 20-40 years.
- Fare is positively correlated with survival.
- Heatmap shows Pclass and Fare are strongly correlated.
- Gender, Pclass, and Fare are key factors affecting survival.
"""
print(summary)
